# Merge Triplets to Form Target Triplet

## Difficulty
Medium

## Approach
A triplet can only contribute to the answer if none of its values exceed the corresponding value in `target`.

For each valid triplet:
- If one of its coordinates matches the target at that position, record that index.
- Maintain a set `good` containing the indices (`0`, `1`, `2`) that have been matched.

At the end:
- If all three indices have been matched, the target triplet can be formed by merging those valid triplets.
- Otherwise, it is impossible.

The merge operation takes the maximum value at each position, so as long as every target coordinate is supplied by some valid triplet, the merged result will equal the target.

## Complexity
- **Time Complexity:** `O(n)`
- **Space Complexity:** `O(1)`

> Although a set is used, it stores at most three indices, so the extra space is constant.

## Code

```python
class Solution:
    def mergeTriplets(self, triplets, target):
        good = set()

        for t in triplets:
            if (t[0] > target[0] or t[1] > target[1] or t[2] > target[2]):
                continue

            for i, v in enumerate(t):
                if v == target[i]:
                    good.add(i)

        return len(good) == 3
```
